SIMPLE: parson
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Parson
<hw>Par"son</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>persone</ets> person, parson, OF. <ets>persone</ets>, F.
<ets>personne</ets> person, LL. <ets>persona</ets> (sc.
<ets>ecclesiae</ets>), fr. L. <ets>persona</ets> a person. See
<er>Person</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Eng. Eccl. Law)</fld> <def>A person who represents
a parish in its ecclesiastical and corporate capacities; hence, the
rector or incumbent of a parochial church, who has full possession of
all the rights thereof, with the cure of souls.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any clergyman having ecclesiastical preferment; one
who is in orders, or is licensed to preach; a preacher.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He hears the <qex>parson</qex> pray and preach.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Parson bird</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a New
Zealand bird (<spn>Prosthemadera Nov⟦ae⟧seelandi⟦ae⟧</spn>) remarkable
for its powers of mimicry and its ability to articulate words. Its color
is glossy black, with a curious tuft of long, curly, white feathers on
each side of the throat. It is often kept as a cage bird.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Parsonage</ent>⟦br⟧
